Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ek.seˈkuː.toː/, [ɛk.s̠ɛˈkuː.t̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ek.seˈku.to/, [ɛk.sɛˈkuː.t̪ɔ]

Etymology 1[edit]

From exsecūtus, past participle of exsequor, from ex- (“out”) + sequor (“to follow”).

Participle[edit]

execūtō

  1. dative masculine singular of execūtus
  2. dative neuter singular of execūtus
  3. ablative masculine singular of execūtus
  4. ablative neuter singular of execūtus

Etymology 2[edit]

Alternative forms[edit]

  • exsecūtō (Medieval Latin)

Verb[edit]

execūtō (present infinitive execūtāre, perfect active execūtāvī, supine execūtātum); first conjugation

  1. (Medieval Latin) to execute (enact or carry out)
  2. (Medieval Latin) to execute (carry out a death sentence)
